[[Category:Watercolor paintings]] [[Category:Martha Burchfield]] [[Category:1972 paintings]] [[Category:American Impressionism]] [[Category:Water in art]]

The '''succession tracts''' of the Elizabethan period, continuing into the reign of [[James I of England]], debated the legal status, and other attributes, of candidates to [[succession to Elizabeth I of England|succeed Elizabeth I of England]].
==Early tracts== {|border=1 !Year !Author !Title !Comment |- |1563<ref name="Kim2000">{{cite book|author=Keechang Kim|title=Aliens in Medieval Law: The Origins of Modern Citizenship|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QidHO7WfRxMC&pg=PA175|date=7 December 2000|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-80085-3|pages=175–}}</ref> |[[John Hales (died 1572)|John Hales]] |''Declaration'' |An innovative treatise, it argued against [[Mary Queen of Scots]] and [[Margaret Douglas]], and pushed forward the claim of [[Lady Catherine Grey]].<ref name="Archer2003">{{cite book|author=Ian W. Archer|title=Religion, Politics, and Society in Sixteenth-Century England|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r44plPoT3bIC&pg=PA47|year=2003|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-81867-4|page=47}}</ref> |- |1565 |Anonymous |''Allegations against the surmised title of the Queen of Scotland''<ref name="Kim2000"/> |Printed, but extant only in manuscript. It supported the Suffolk claim, insisted on Scotland as foreign country, and cited the precedent of [[John of England]], who succeeded ahead of [[Arthur I, Duke of Brittany]] who was foreign born.<ref>{{cite book |author=Marie Axton |title=The Queen's Two Bodies |year=1977 |publisher=Royal Historical Society |page=25 note}}</ref> |- |1565(?) |[[Anthony Browne (justice)|Anthony Browne]]<ref name="Kim2000"/> | | |- |1566 | |''An Answer to "Allegations against ..."''<ref name="Kim2000"/> | |- |1566, or 1565<ref name="Phillips1964">{{cite book|author=James Emerson Phillips|title=Images of a Queen: Mary Stuart in Sixteenth-century Literature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0A8KFf0xfNoC&pg=PA244|year=1964|publisher=University of California Press|pages=244–|id=GGKEY:EA73RFGGGEA}}</ref> | |Anti-Suffolk tract<ref name="Kim2000"/> |[[William Atwood]] attributed it to a Thomas Morgan (T. M.).<ref name="Phillips1964"/> |- |1566 |Anonymous |"A Letter"<ref name="Kim2000"/> | |- |1567 |[[Edmund Plowden]], unpublished<ref name="Kim2000"/> |''A Treatise ... Proving the Queen of Scots by her Birth is Not Disabled by the Law of England [...]''<ref name="Warnicke2006">{{cite book|author=Retha M. Warnicke|title=Mary Queen of Scots|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i8kD_XkHcNcC&pg=PA98|date=28 July 2006|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-203-08848-7|page=98}}</ref> |Against Hales, Plowden argues that the statute of Edward III, on aliens and inheritance, cannot be applied to the [[body politic]] involved in the succession.<ref name="Warnicke2006"/> [[William Maitland of Lethington]], acting for Mary, had anticipated to [[William Cecil, 1st Baron Burghley|William Cecil]] the application of the [[common law]] to the issue.<ref>{{cite book |author=Marie Axton |title=The Queen's Two Bodies |year=1977 |publisher=Royal Historical Society |page=18}}</ref> |- |1569 |[[John Lesley]]<ref name="Kim2000"/> | |Adapted arguments from Plowden and Browne.<ref>{{cite book |author=Marie Axton |title=The Queen's Two Bodies |year=1977 |publisher=Royal Historical Society |page=20}}</ref> |- |1571 |Robert Heighington |''A Treatise on the Succession'' (inferred; these unpublished notes were made public by Doleman) |In favour of the line through the House of Portugal. Robert Heighington or Highington of [[Richmond, Yorkshire]] was secretary to the [[Thomas Percy, 7th Earl of Northumberland|Earl of Northumberland]].<ref name="EE">{{cite book|author=[[Edward Edwards (librarian)|Edward Edwards]]|title=The Life of Sir Walter Ralegh: Together with His Letters: Now First Collected|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OOA6AAAAcAAJ&pg=PA288|year=1868|page=288}}</ref> He was indicted for treason and went into exile in the [[Low Countries]] after the [[Rising of the North]] of 1569, as one of the more prosperous rebels.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Christopher Dyer|author2=Andrew Hopper|author3=Evelyn Lord|author4=Nigel Tringham|title=New Directions in Local History Since Hoskins|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mWgRSqr_63sC&pg=PA180|year=2011|publisher=Univ of Hertfordshire Press|isbn=978-1-907396-53-3|page=180}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Memorials|title=Memorials of the Rebellion of 1569 ed. by Sir C. Sharp|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OXoEAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA229|year=1840|pages=229–30}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=Philip II (King of Spain)|author2=Louis-Prosper Gachard|title=Correspondance de Philippe II sur les affaires des Pays-Bas 1558-1577|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P95LAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA232|year=1858|publisher=Librairie ancienne et moderne|page=232|language=fr}}</ref> He supplied maps from 1583 to the [[Spanish Armada]],<ref>{{cite book |author=[[Geoffrey Parker (historian)|Geoffrey Parker]]|title=Success is Never Final|year=2002 |publisher=Basic Books |isbn=046505477-3 |page=110}}</ref> and was a correspondent of [[Francis Englefield]].<ref>{{cite book|author=British museum|title=Catalogue of the Harleian Manuscripts in the British Museum|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vvJplqs_XX8C&pg=PA173|year=1808|page=173}}</ref> He made arguments found in Lesley, adding the precedence of John of Gaunt over Richard II for the succession.<ref name="EE"/> |}
==Later tracts== A statute of 1581 forbade in terms publication on, and other discussion of, the succession.<ref>{{cite book|author=Barbara Rosen|title=Witchcraft in England, 1558-1618|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1Ij_8vgoKPgC&pg=PA56|year=1969|publisher=Univ of Massachusetts Press|isbn=978-0-87023-753-9|pages=56–7}}</ref>
{|border=1 !Year !Author !Title !Comment |- |1580s | |''Certaine Errours''<ref name="Kim2000"/> | |- |1584 |Anonymous |''[[Leycester's Commonwealth]]''<ref>{{cite book|author=Ethan H. Shagan|title=Catholics and the 'Protestant Nation': Religious Politics and Identity in Early Modern England|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ajZ0tj7tYtAC&pg=PA81|date=3 September 2005|publisher=Manchester University Press|isbn=978-0-7190-5768-7|page=81}}</ref> |Known otherwise initially<ref name="Kim2000"/> |- |c.1587 |[[George Puttenham]]<ref name="Breaking37">{{cite book |editor=Jean-Christophe Mayer|title=Breaking the Silence on the Succession: A sourcebook of manuscripts and rare texts, c.1587–1603|year=2003|publisher=Astræa Texts|isbn=2-84269-566-6|pages=37–40}}</ref> |''Justificacion'' |In a number of manuscripts, it considers the succession position of the 1580s, with attempted objectivity.<ref name="Breaking37"/> It defends the execution of Mary Queen of Scots.<ref>{{cite ODNB|id=22913|title=Puttenham, George|first=Steven W.|last=May}}</ref> |- |1594 |R. Doleman (now thought to be a [[collective pseudonym]] for a group around [[Robert Persons]], to whom the work was attributed at the time) |''[[A Conference about the Next Succession to the Crowne of Ingland]]'' |An analysis of around 14 succession candidates, in terms of five lineages with royal pretensions (including the [[House of Aviz]]). <ref>Mayer p. 92.</ref> This work put into play the succession, by suggesting that [[elective monarchy]], rather than [[hereditary monarchy]], was a more appropriate way to address the succession issue. That approach was rebutted in most of the subsequent tracts.<ref name="Houl35">{{cite book|author=Ralph Anthony Houlbrooke|title=James VI and I: Ideas, Authority, and Government|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3hBSj8wodKcC&pg=PA35|year=2006|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-0-7546-5410-0|page=35}}</ref> |- |1598 |[[Alexander Dicsone]] |''Of the Right of the Crowne efter Hir Majesty''<ref>Mayer p. 91, 99-100</ref> |Commissioned by James VI, in answer to Doleman, with a related work by [[Walter Quin]]. Quin had made an oration on James's claim in 1596; but his book of 1598 on the same topic was refused by the printer, [[Robert Waldegrave]].<ref>{{cite ODNB|id=22964|title=Quin, Walter|first=J. K.|last= McGinley}}</ref> [[Edmund Ashfield (Catholic agent)|Edmund Ashfield]] had prompted James to respond to Doleman, stating that the literature in favour of his mother Mary Queen of Scots was now counter-productive. He urged James to make a case attractive to influential [[common lawyer]]s.<ref>{{cite book |author=Marie Axton |title=The Queen's Two Bodies |year=1977 |publisher=Royal Historical Society |page=95}}</ref>
Dicsone's work dealt with the four major points raised against James's claim: (a) Scottish birth; (b) the provisions of the [[will of Henry VIII]]; (c) the attainder of [[Mary, Queen of Scots]] his mother; (d) his cadet status in the [[House of Lancaster]].<ref>Mayer p. 101.</ref> |- |1598 |[[Peter Wentworth]], posthumous publication |''A Pithie Exhortation'' |Smuggled out of England, perhaps by [[Sir David Foulis, 1st Baronet|David Foulis]]; printed in Scotland by Robert Waldegrave.<ref name="M99">Mayer p. 99</ref> |- |1598 |James VI of Scotland |''The Trew Law of Free Monarchies'' |This work, known for its support of the [[divine right of kings]], was also an intervention in the succession debate, through its rejection of the [[resistance theory]] in the tract of Doleman, and of the role of parliaments in determining succession.<ref name="M99"/> |- |1598–9 |[[William Watson (priest)|William Watson]] | |Watson claimed to have written a treatise circulated to the Privy Council, the queen and the [[Robert Devereux, 2nd Earl of Essex|Earl of Essex]], against the [[Jesuit]] line on a Spanish succession in Doleman. It favoured the [[House of York]], the claim through the House of Aviz being Lancastrian. Watson was an Appellant in the [[Archpriest Controversy]] of these years.<ref name="Gajda">{{cite book|author=Alexandra Gajda|title=The Earl of Essex and Late Elizabethan Political Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qCJsTZDIElYC&pg=PA139|date=15 March 2012|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-969968-1|page=139}}</ref> |- |c.1599 |Pseudonymous (Don Biud de Haro, translator Harye Bedwod)<ref name="Ungerer1976"/> |''Anatomie of Spayne'' |It was another and painstaking case built up against the Spanish claim.<ref name="Gajda"/> The background to the Spanish original of the ''Anatomie'', translated for Essex (by, it is thought, [[Arthur Atye]]), is opaque, but it has been attributed to the Portuguese Dominican José Teixeira in the train of [[Antonio Pérez (statesman)|Antonio Pérez]].<ref name="Ungerer1976">{{cite book|author=Gustav Ungerer|title=A Spaniard in Elizabethan England: The Correspondence of Antonio Pérez's Exile|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LZCorYDvETQC&pg=PA275|date=January 1976|publisher=Tamesis Books|isbn=978-0-7293-0021-6|page=275}}</ref> |- |c.1599 |Irenicus Philodikaios<ref name="M111">Mayer p. 111.</ref> |''A Treatise'' |A low-profile printed work supporting James's claim, thought to be by an English writer.<ref>{{cite book|author=Ralph Anthony Houlbrooke|title=James VI and I: Ideas, Authority, and Government|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3hBSj8wodKcC&pg=PA34|year=2006|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-0-7546-5410-0|page=34}}</ref> The main focus was on Doleman's use of the "Act of Association" (a misnomer). It made play of the misleading application of the [[Safety of the Queen, etc. Act 1584]] to the case of James, given his lack of involvement in subverting Elizabeth.<ref>Mayer p. 106.</ref> |- |c.1599 |Sir Edmund Ashfield, an agent of James.<ref>{{cite book |editor=Jean-Christophe Mayer|title=Breaking the Silence on the Succession: A sourcebook of manuscripts and rare texts, c.1587–1603|year=2003|publisher=Astræa Texts|isbn=2-84269-566-6|pages=189–92}}</ref> Possibly therefore [[Edmund Ashfield (Catholic agent)|Edmund Ashfield]]. (Details of the name and identification are unclear in the reference; Sir William Eure and Sir Edmund Ashfield were imprisoned in 1601, for communicating with James on the subject of the succession.)<ref>{{cite book|author1=Elizabeth I (Queen of England)|author2=James I (King of England)|title=Letters of Queen Elizabeth and King James VI. of Scotland: Some of Them Printed from Originals in the Possession of the Rev. Edward Ryder, and Others from a Ms. which Formerly Belonged to Sir Peter Thompson, Kt|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Bv4UAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA136|year=1849|publisher=Camden Society|page=136}}</ref> | |Manuscript addressed to James, analysing social groups in England and how to win them over. |- |1600 |[[John Colville (c. 1540–1605)|John Colville]] |''Palinod'' |A retraction by Colville of an earlier work that had denied James's claim, printed by Robert Charteras.<ref name="Houl35"/> Colville had called James a bastard. [[John Spottiswoode]] asserted that Colville was not the real author.<ref>{{cite ODNB|id=6011|title=Colville, John|first=Rob|last=Macpherson}}</ref> |- |1600 |[[Henry Constable]] |''Discoverye of a Counterfecte Conference … for Thadvancement of a Counterfecte Tytle'' |Published in Paris, though it claimed to be published in Cologne. Against Doleman; Constable was a Catholic convert who supported James's claim.<ref>{{Cite ODNB |title = Constable, Henry (1562–1613)|last = Sullivan|first = Ceri|id = 6103|accessdate = 7 February 2014}}</ref> |- |c.1600 |Anonymous |''An Apologie of the Scottische King'' |Against Doleman, and intended for a broad audience, it warned against a disputed succession. Left in manuscript.<ref name="M111"/> It has been suggested that the author was a Scot living in England.<ref>Mayer p. 91.</ref> |- |1601, then revised |[[Henry Hooke (archdeacon)|Henry Hooke]], later Archdeacon of York. |''Of the succession against the Crowne of England'' |A manuscript eventually submitted to James VI, it was a reply to Doleman that pointed up dangers from Catholics and malcontents.<ref>{{cite book |editor=Jean-Christophe Mayer|title=Breaking the Silence on the Succession: A sourcebook of manuscripts and rare texts, c.1587–1603|year=2003|publisher=Astræa Texts|isbn=2-84269-566-6|pages=261–6}}</ref> |- |1602 |[[John Harington (writer)|John Harington]] |''Tract on the Succession to the Crown'' |Printed 1880,<ref name="Kim2000"/> edited by [[Clements Robert Markham]]. It makes a case based on the ''Epistle'' (1548) of [[Protector Somerset]], Wentworth and Doleman.<ref>''A tract on the succession to the crown (A.D. 1602)'' (1880) p. 4, edited by Clements Robert Markham for the [[Roxburghe Club]]; [https://archive.org/stream/cu31924030506319#page/n59/mode/2up archive.org.]</ref> |- |1602<ref name="Houl35"/> |[[Thomas Craig (jurist)|Sir Thomas Craig]] |{{la icon}} ''The Right of Succession to the Kingdom of England''<ref>{{cite book|author=John F. McDiarmid|title=The Monarchical Republic of Early Modern England: Essays in Response to Patrick Collinson|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4jDjxxyp4mkC&pg=PA168|date=1 January 2007|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-0-7546-8758-0|pages=168–70}}</ref> |Against Doleman. The work was first published in its English translation by [[James Gadderar]], in 1703.<ref>{{cite DNB|wstitle=Gadderar, James|volume=20}}</ref> |}
